05936nam a22008655i 9780674279971DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20222022mau    fo  d z      eng d  a97806742799717 a10.4159/97806742799712doi  a(DE-B1597)634071  a(OCoLC)1341444812  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  amaucUS-MA 7aBIO0260002bisacsh04a974.70049242231 aRabinowitz, Richard, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aObjects of Love and Regret :bA Brooklyn Story /cRichard Rabinowitz. 1aCambridge, MA : bHarvard University Press, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (352 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tRabinowitz Family -- tIntroduction -- t1 Sarah Buys a Bottle Opener -- t2 Isaac Guss Finds an Artillery Shell -- t3 Papa Doesn’t Know from Ice Cream -- t4 Shenka Puts Pencils Away in a Cigar Box -- t5 Dave Splurges on a Bottle of Perfume -- t6 Sarah Awaits the Mailman’s Whistle -- t7 Beverly Is Startled by the Scissors -- t8 Dave Takes Out the Beach Chairs -- t9 Richard Puts a Record on the Magnavox -- t10 Sarah Warms Up Her Coffee on a Hot Plate -- t11 Dave Never Has to Rewind the Clock -- tFurther Reading -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAn award-winning historian and museum curator tells the story of his Jewish immigrant family by lovingly reconstructing its dramatic encounters with the memory-filled objects of ordinary life.At a pushcart stall in East New York, Brooklyn, in the spring of 1934, eighteen-year-old Sarah Schwartz bought her mother, Shenka, a green, wooden-handled bottle opener. Decades later, Sarah would tear up telling her son Richard, “Your bubbe always worked so hard. Twenty cents, it cost me.”How could that unremarkable item, and others like it, reveal the untold history of a Jewish immigrant family, their chances and their choices over the course of an eventful century? By unearthing the personal meaning and historical significance of simple everyday objects, Richard Rabinowitz offers an intimate portrait connecting Sarah, Shenka, and the rest of his family to the twentieth-century transformations of American life. During the Depression, Sarah—born on a Polish battlefield in World War I, scarred by pogroms, pressed too early into adult responsibilities—receives a gift of French perfume, her fiancé Dave’s response to the stigma of poverty. Later we watch Dave load folding chairs into his car for a state-park outing, signaling both the postwar detachment from city life and his own escape from failures to be a good “provider” for those he loves.Objects of Love and Regret is closely wedded to the lives of American Jewish immigrants and their children, yet Rabinowitz invites all of us to contemplate the material world that anchors our own memories. Beautifully written, absorbing, and emotionally vivid, this is a memoir that brings us back to the striving, the dreams, the successes, and the tragedies that are part of every family’s story.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aImmigrantszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewsxMaterial culturezNew York (State)zNew York. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszNew York (State)zNew YorkxSocial life and customsy20th century. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Personal Memoirs.2bisacsh  a1930s Movies.  aAnti-Semitism.  aBrooklyn Navy Yard.  aBrownsville.  aCold War.  aEast New York.  aFamily History.  aImmigrants.  aJewish Cooking.  aJews.  aLower East Side.  aMaterial Culture.  aMothers.  aNew York City.  aSynagogue.  aTenements.  aWomen’s work.  aWorld War I.  aWorld War II.08iTitle is part of eBook package: